e in Loire-Atlantique. The surname <i>Breillard</i> is very rare in France.","French (<b>Bréard</b>): metathesized form of <b>Bérard</b> (see   Berard  )."]},{"name":"Lepine","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Marcel, Emile, Jacques, Donat, Fernand, Gaston, Gilfred, Gilles, Henri, Normand.","French (<b>Lépine</b>): from <i>l'épine</i> ‘the thorn’, used as a soldier's name.","French (<b>Lépine</b>): topographic name, with fused definite article <i>l(a)</i>, from Old French <i>espine</i> (from Latin <i>spina</i>) ‘thorn bush’, or a habitational name from any of several places in various parts of France called Lépine or L'Épine, named with this word."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":26,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":51,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Becard was born in 1264, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Pieter Piers Becard, was 19 and his mother, Alice Greystoke, was 19. He had at least 1 daughter with Alice Greystoke. He died on 29 November 1325, in Burton Leonard, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 6